{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d2828808-1807-4a40-bfd2-1f22104f6d79","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` is not a built-in .NET MAUI property on `ContentPage`. To go truly edge-to-edge, you need two things:\n\n**1. Set `IgnoreSafeArea` on the view itself (iOS):**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\" ...>\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**2. Enable edge-to-edge on Android:**\n\nIn your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n}\n```\n\n> **Note:** On .NET 10 targeting Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but you still need `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` for older API levels.\n\n**Also check:**\n- If your page is in a `NavigationPage` or `Shell`, hide the nav bar: `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` or `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"`\n- Make sure no parent layout (e.g., `Grid`, `VerticalStackLayout`) has `Padding` or `Margin` set.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7da0ce37-52de-4f03-b808-528e7a7f1fdd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Let me think about what they might be missing:\n\n1. In .NET MAUI, `IgnoreSafeArea` is the property that controls whether content extends behind system UI (status bar, navigation bar). \n2. `SafeAreaEdges` on ContentPage controls which edges the page respects safe areas for - but there's also the need to handle the individual view level.\n\n\n3. For Android specifically, the app needs to be configured to draw edge-to-edge behind system bars, and on iOS the safe area insets need to be ignored at the view level.\n\nThe user's mention of `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is puzzling since that property doesn't seem standard in .NET MAUI—it might be from the Community Toolkit or a custom implementation they're using.\n\nLooking at the next thinking, the core issue is likely that `IgnoreSafeArea` needs to be applied directly to the Image view or its parent layout rather than just at the page level, and on Android they may need to ensure edge-to-edge rendering is enabled. If they're using NavigationPage or Shell, those containers could also be adding unwanted spacing that's preventing the image from truly filling the screen. the ContentPage. Additionally, on Android, they may need to enable edge-to-edge mode explicitly.\n\nWait, I need to reconsider what `SafeAreaEdges` actually is. I'm not confident that's a real property on ContentPage in .NET MAUI—the user might be referencing something custom or mixing up terminology.\n\nFor edge-to-edge in .NET MAUI, the actual approach differs by platform. On iOS, I'd set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the view or its container. On Android with .NET 9+, edge-to-edge is the default for Android 15 and newer, but for older versions I'd need to call `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` through platform-specific code, though there might be built-in support in newer versions that handles this automatically.","outputTokens":1295,"requestId":"482A:262BA4:C2ABD3:E18DF1:69F3FDD0"},"id":"86415f39-eacd-4efe-b924-f6fb545feab4","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:12:08.753Z","parentId":"8d9040fb-5393-4b78-828c-d55c3973ac6b"}
